c and private finance necessary to prevent an impending planetary catastrophe. The first section of the handbook introduces readers to the origins and evolution of sustainable development. An examination of public and private finance follows in the next two sections, presented from the perspectives of authors from both ‘developed’ and ‘developing’ countries. Climate change, one of the largest sectors of finance for sustainable development, is investigated in detail, as is the new and emerging development frontier, the ‘blue’ economy of the world’s oceans. Suitable for students, policymakers and the public at large, the handbook highlights the lessons learned and points the way forward for sustainable development and finance in the wake of the global pandemic, and the challenges to come.  aIssued also in print.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 0aSustainable developmentxEconomic aspects. 0aSustainable developmentxFinance. 4aKlimawandel. 4aNachhaltige Entwicklung. 4aNachhaltige Finanzierung. 7aBUSINESS & ECONOMICS / Finance / General.2bisacsh  aCOVID-19.  aClimate change.  aFinancial management and Investment.  aFiscal policy.  aPublic finance.  aSustainable development.  ablue economy.1 aAhlström, Hanna, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBasak, Bishwajit, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBose, Arnab, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBradley, Tony, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBreakey, Hugh, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBuckwell, Andrew, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCadman, Timothy, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCadman, Timothy, eeditor.4e